1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,700
Good day, dear viewers.

2
00:00:03,280 --> 00:00:11,740
Today we'll examine a circuit designed for controlling a Tesla transformer based on a half-bridge inverter.

3
00:00:13,060 --> 00:00:30,840
The master generator is assembled on the TL494 chip, and its frequency with ratings of 150 pF and 10 kOhm resistance can change in the range from 230 kHz to 640 kHz.

4
00:00:31,400 --> 00:00:47,860
I don't recommend making Tesla transformers with frequency below 200 kHz, since at this frequency the skin effect on human skin already disappears, and current is then able to penetrate under the skin causing internal burns.

5
00:00:48,100 --> 00:00:50,220
That is, below 200 kHz we don't go.

6
00:00:52,420 --> 00:01:07,380
Also, the chip when it works in push-pull mode — the maximum operating range in such a connection I managed to push to 680-700 kHz.

7
00:01:07,840 --> 00:01:12,840
That is, if you use this variant, we won't be able to go above this frequency.

8
00:01:13,300 --> 00:01:16,600
There's such a frequency damper.

9
00:01:17,600 --> 00:01:29,000
Further, after the chip and the outputs, the signal goes to the TC4093 chip on which the modulation system is assembled.

10
00:01:29,840 --> 00:01:36,420
The modulating signal we take through an HCPL3120 opto-driver.

11
00:01:37,920 --> 00:01:45,000
This driver is installed here for the purpose of protecting our lab generator from high-frequency pickups.

12
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:48,000
Here there's optical isolation.

13
00:01:48,220 --> 00:01:52,440
And pay attention, I marked common generator and common signal.

14
00:01:52,880 --> 00:01:56,200
The generator common nowhere connects to common in the scheme.

15
00:01:56,340 --> 00:01:59,680
That is, we have full system isolation.

16
00:01:59,840 --> 00:02:10,780
If your rectangular pulse generator has an amplitude of 5 volts, then we put a resistance of 120 Ohm at the input.

17
00:02:10,780 --> 00:02:16,680
If amplitude is 12-15 V, then resistance is 360 Ohm.

18
00:02:17,460 --> 00:02:25,660
Further, the modulating signal from the HCPL3120 driver is supplied through a 47 Ohm current-limiting resistor to a switch.

19
00:02:26,240 --> 00:02:38,500
The switch is introduced into the scheme so we could switch the whole system to continuous work mode or work in burst mode with the modulation frequency that's at the input.

20
00:02:39,380 --> 00:02:47,320
Signal modulation is done directly on the TC4093 chip, since at its input it has logic two.

21
00:02:47,480 --> 00:02:56,560
That is, if there's a logical one at each input of the logic element, the signal passes through.

22
00:02:56,680 --> 00:03:00,900
If one and logical zero, the signal doesn't pass.

23
00:03:01,180 --> 00:03:03,360
With this we do modulation.

24
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:12,660
See that the modulating signal comes to pin 1 of the logic element, and the signal from the chip comes to pin 2.

25
00:03:12,660 --> 00:03:23,460
The logic element is inverting here, so from the output we need to supply to one more logic element and flip this signal.

26
00:03:23,560 --> 00:03:27,080
That is, back from logical zero to logical one.

27
00:03:27,080 --> 00:03:35,380
This way we get an analog of the signal that we had at the output of the TL494 chip.

28
00:03:35,860 --> 00:03:43,080
And further this signal comes to the IR2110 or IR2113 driver.

29
00:03:44,880 --> 00:03:55,220
This chip is a push-pull driver capable of working in half-bridge scheme mode with bootstrap power.

30
00:03:56,220 --> 00:04:01,480
A driver up to 2 A in pulse, not too powerful.

31
00:04:02,360 --> 00:04:05,420
So, here are the main moments.

32
00:04:05,920 --> 00:04:08,480
Here we have a bootstrap diode.

33
00:04:08,540 --> 00:04:15,420
I used a diode of brand UF4007, a fast-acting diode with 1000 V voltage.

34
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:19,680
And pay special attention to this capacitor.

35
00:04:19,860 --> 00:04:22,660
I marked it — tantalum capacitor.

36
00:04:22,660 --> 00:04:24,900
Desirable to find exactly this kind here.

37
00:04:25,840 --> 00:04:29,740
Its parameters are somewhere about 20 µF, 25 V.

38
00:04:30,020 --> 00:04:38,060
If you can't find such in stores, put an electrolytic here, also at 20-25 µF, quality.

39
00:04:38,700 --> 00:04:46,140
And parallel to it put a high-quality film capacitor, somewhere 2-5 µF.

40
00:04:47,480 --> 00:04:50,500
You can replace this tantalum capacitor this way.

41
00:04:51,500 --> 00:04:54,400
And the next important moment.

42
00:04:54,560 --> 00:04:55,420
Here it's marked.

43
00:04:55,500 --> 00:05:04,340
When the scheme works in continuous mode, track the temperature of the power keys driver, smoothly raising the supply voltage on the keys.

44
00:05:04,800 --> 00:05:06,300
This is the very main moment.

45
00:05:06,480 --> 00:05:10,500
The operating temperature of this driver is up to 150 degrees.

46
00:05:10,500 --> 00:05:21,840
Briefly, if this is a branded driver, not a Chinese fake, it can withstand overloads up to 300 degrees for 10 seconds.

47
00:05:21,980 --> 00:05:25,560
But I don't recommend subjecting it to such a test.

48
00:05:26,620 --> 00:05:30,860
I, say, hold this chip in a mode up to 100 degrees.

49
00:05:31,860 --> 00:05:35,340
So, I track this moment.

50
00:05:35,660 --> 00:05:40,980
Otherwise there's a risk that the driver will fail from internal thermal breakdown.

51
00:05:43,180 --> 00:05:48,660
Smoothly raise voltage on the keys and track the temperature.

52
00:05:48,760 --> 00:05:50,000
This is a very important moment.

53
00:05:50,000 --> 00:06:01,300
The transistors used in our half-bridge scheme will be the IRF series with a rating of possible voltage from 100 volts.

54
00:06:01,520 --> 00:06:06,260
This is the voltage between source and drain of the FET key.

55
00:06:06,940 --> 00:06:09,220
This is the source point — source.

56
00:06:10,880 --> 00:06:25,700
So, 100 V for us — this is the IRF510, and the maximum rating for which the 2113 driver is designed is work with supplied voltage of 600 volts.

57
00:06:26,240 --> 00:06:33,580
The 2110 driver — 500 volts can be supplied at the power keys input up to this value.

58
00:06:36,100 --> 00:06:45,900
I recommend using the final transistor from the IRF series, this is the IRF840 — I applied it here in my scheme.

59
00:06:47,500 --> 00:06:52,660
Further we see that here a divider is assembled on two capacitors.

60
00:06:53,380 --> 00:07:01,020
These capacitors are desirable to take of big dimensions — I took at 630 volts, 4.7 µF.

61
00:07:01,020 --> 00:07:04,360
They also form for us the middle point.

62
00:07:05,200 --> 00:07:15,240
The feature of the half-bridge scheme is that it divides the input voltage applied to the keys in half at this point.

63
00:07:16,120 --> 00:07:21,720
If you wish, this half-bridge scheme can very easily be converted into a full bridge.

64
00:07:21,720 --> 00:07:25,760
For this purpose take one more analogous driver.

65
00:07:26,420 --> 00:07:32,620
Assembled also this whole part with power keys and connected only these capacitors.

66
00:07:33,840 --> 00:07:38,280
And the connection is all exactly the same as in this scheme.

67
00:07:38,360 --> 00:07:45,740
Only there the control signal is supplied diagonally.

68
00:07:45,740 --> 00:07:57,160
If here we see that from pin 11 to pin 10, then on the second chip the signal will be supplied from pin 11 to pin 12.

69
00:07:57,220 --> 00:08:01,840
That is, supply diagonally so our keys also worked diagonally.

70
00:08:02,360 --> 00:08:12,200
Between the middle point that the capacitor dividers form and the middle point between the power keys is located our load.

71
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:17,360
In this case where this scheme was applied — this is the Tesla transformer inductor.

72
00:08:18,080 --> 00:08:33,560
Since our inductor has a length on the order of several meters, in the range of 3-4, small resistance, small inductance, currents through power keys in continuous mode of the scheme's work can be significant.

73
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:40,940
Generally, this scheme was developed specifically for work in modulation mode.

74
00:08:40,940 --> 00:08:53,060
Since when the Tesla transformer works in continuous mode, all the interesting moments connected with the interaction of the Tesla transformer with the surrounding environment aren't observed at us.

75
00:08:54,060 --> 00:09:01,380
So here it's applied in work with modulation.

76
00:09:01,380 --> 00:09:15,700
Whoever will operate a Tesla transformer in continuous mode without modulation, then you must definitely track temperature here — an important moment so as not to burn the driver.

77
00:09:16,460 --> 00:09:24,940
And this inductor wound to bigger meterage, picked according to your Tesla transformer.

78
00:09:25,480 --> 00:09:29,640
Now let's examine our device directly in iron.

79
00:09:29,640 --> 00:09:39,760
I made this build in the form of an etagere so I could do convenient repair if needed.

80
00:09:40,100 --> 00:09:53,980
In the upper part of the device is the control — the TL494 chip, TC4093, and the HCPL3120 opto-driver.

81
00:09:53,980 --> 00:09:58,800
This is the switch shown on the scheme that turns on modulation.

82
00:09:59,700 --> 00:10:04,420
And see here two multi-turn trim resistors.

83
00:10:05,080 --> 00:10:15,180
One resistor is responsible for frequency, this is the 10 kOhm, and the other resistor is responsible for the duration of control signals.

84
00:10:16,180 --> 00:10:29,220
Also if marked here as pulse duration — change the duration of control signals, this way we can limit the current at the output of our half-bridge inverter.

85
00:10:30,380 --> 00:10:36,640
This is one of the variants of adjustment that can be done in this scheme.

86
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:44,700
This is the regulator, the stabilizer, and auxiliary capacitors.

87
00:10:44,940 --> 00:10:56,640
The keys are located on heat sinks opposite each other on dielectric substrates smeared with thermal paste.

88
00:10:58,500 --> 00:11:07,420
This is how the 4.7 µF capacitors at 630 V look — here is the pair of them.

89
00:11:07,920 --> 00:11:10,680
Here is one capacitor, and there inside is the second.

90
00:11:11,400 --> 00:11:16,140
This is all assembled on one board, directly with the power keys.

91
00:11:17,040 --> 00:11:20,980
Here you can see the IR2113 driver.

92
00:11:20,980 --> 00:11:32,900
And from the bottom of the scheme is screwed the DC-DC converter that converts 12 V from the battery to 16 V.

93
00:11:33,360 --> 00:11:43,640
I try to work with a voltage of 16-18 V so there'd be quality opening of the power key gates.

94
00:11:43,640 --> 00:11:50,140
If you don't have such a converter, it can also be acquired separately in radio stores.

95
00:11:50,420 --> 00:11:57,840
Then you can apply 12 V directly from the battery at this power point.

96
00:11:58,400 --> 00:12:01,980
The scheme will work, nothing scary will happen.

97
00:12:02,420 --> 00:12:05,580
I simply apply such systems — more convenient.

98
00:12:05,620 --> 00:12:11,980
Here full galvanic isolation, and I can connect such a homemade converter.

99
00:12:11,980 --> 00:12:17,760
To the lab power supply, and not to the battery.

100
00:12:19,500 --> 00:12:23,340
So, in principle there's nothing more here.

101
00:12:23,660 --> 00:12:32,480
Here as positioned to each other on dielectric substrates smeared with thermal paste.

102
00:12:33,980 --> 00:12:41,780
So, this is how the 4.7 µF 630 V capacitors look.

103
00:12:41,980 --> 00:12:46,100
Here is one capacitor, and there inside is the second.

104
00:12:46,760 --> 00:12:51,600
This is all assembled on one board, directly with the power keys.

105
00:12:52,460 --> 00:12:56,420
Here you can see the IR2113 driver.

106
00:12:57,380 --> 00:13:02,240
And from the bottom of the scheme is screwed exactly the DC-DC converter.

107
00:13:02,320 --> 00:13:08,300
This one, which converts 12 V from the battery to 16 V.

108
00:13:08,300 --> 00:13:18,300
I try to work with 16-18 V voltage so there'd be quality opening of power key gates.

109
00:13:19,240 --> 00:13:25,560
But if you don't have such a converter, it can also be acquired separately in radio stores.

110
00:13:25,780 --> 00:13:33,260
Then you can apply 12 V directly from the battery at this power point.

111
00:13:33,820 --> 00:13:37,400
The scheme will work, nothing scary will happen.

112
00:13:38,300 --> 00:13:40,640
It's simply more convenient to apply such systems.

113
00:13:41,100 --> 00:13:53,140
Here full galvanic isolation, and I can connect such a homemade converter to the lab power supply, and not to the battery.

114
00:13:53,540 --> 00:13:55,820
Pay attention to this capacitor.

115
00:13:55,960 --> 00:13:57,300
I recommend to use...

116
00:13:57,820 --> 00:14:00,800
Here it's 150 pF, this is on the scheme.

117
00:14:01,360 --> 00:14:05,200
I recommend to use capacitors with small TKE here.

118
00:14:05,200 --> 00:14:12,700
That is, this coefficient that shows the dependency of capacity drift of a capacitor on ambient temperature.

119
00:14:13,260 --> 00:14:17,120
In this case I used tubular Soviet capacitors.

120
00:14:17,940 --> 00:14:25,360
Now you can use SMD capacitors, available in radio parts in stores.

121
00:14:26,620 --> 00:14:31,900
So, here the modulating signal input is supplied.

122
00:14:32,880 --> 00:14:37,120
Well, and that's all — there's not much more here for us.

123
00:14:38,320 --> 00:14:43,200
Now let's move to viewing oscillograms of our device's work.

124
00:14:43,700 --> 00:14:53,260
So, first I assembled this part of the device fully through the driver power and checked separately.

125
00:14:53,820 --> 00:15:00,260
Now the oscilloscope probes stand at these points, after the 33 Ohm resistor.

126
00:15:02,080 --> 00:15:07,000
Power is supplied to the scheme and we observe the oscillogram.

127
00:15:08,140 --> 00:15:16,620
Here you see that we have two signals, they're antiphase, between them there's a mandatory pause.

128
00:15:17,740 --> 00:15:22,700
We can also check the regulation of frequency and duration.

129
00:15:23,200 --> 00:15:26,600
Now I'll rotate the trim resistor.

130
00:15:27,740 --> 00:15:29,300
The frequency changes for us.

131
00:15:32,880 --> 00:15:34,940
The system works.

132
00:15:35,700 --> 00:15:41,920
Well, and you can also check how the pulse duration changes.

133
00:15:43,720 --> 00:15:50,600
The second trim resistor should change smoothly.

134
00:16:01,740 --> 00:16:04,280
The resistors here are multi-turn.

135
00:16:05,280 --> 00:16:07,500
They won't unscrew to the end.

136
00:16:07,600 --> 00:16:10,720
You can see the pulse clearly changes its duration.

137
00:16:11,540 --> 00:16:13,540
And also in the reverse direction.

138
00:16:15,840 --> 00:16:17,880
Here is our frequency.

139
00:16:19,500 --> 00:16:20,760
Everything works.

140
00:16:20,960 --> 00:16:31,600
Now when switching the switch to modulation mode, the signal should fully disappear because the modulation signal isn't supplied at the input.

141
00:16:31,600 --> 00:16:38,280
Now let's connect the input signal and look at how the scheme will work with its presence.

142
00:16:38,540 --> 00:16:42,720
Switch flipped to modulation mode and I apply the modulating signal.

143
00:16:45,300 --> 00:16:48,940
Here you see a characteristic change.

144
00:16:51,640 --> 00:16:59,740
Now I'll stop the signal and you can see that our scheme has switched to pulse bursts mode.

145
00:17:00,290 --> 00:17:11,020
Since the oscilloscope now isn't synced with the input signal, we'll observe its jerk back and forth.

146
00:17:11,180 --> 00:17:16,300
Now we'll change the duration of the modulating signal.

147
00:17:16,580 --> 00:17:21,740
40%, 30%, 20%, 10%.

148
00:17:23,860 --> 00:17:32,900
The sync caught the signal well and it's visible that we have a burst of pulses.

149
00:17:34,700 --> 00:17:42,820
You can examine on the pause too — also in this burst the signal is clearly in antiphase, doesn't go anywhere.

150
00:17:43,080 --> 00:17:45,000
That is, the system works stably.

151
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:47,060
Further I reduce the duration.

152
00:17:48,340 --> 00:17:54,280
The duration makes only 1%.

153
00:17:55,720 --> 00:17:58,420
Such a short burst.

154
00:17:59,820 --> 00:18:01,560
Further I reduce.

155
00:18:04,760 --> 00:18:07,220
You can examine too.

156
00:18:08,460 --> 00:18:10,680
That is, the system works stably.

157
00:18:10,840 --> 00:18:16,060
There are 4 pulses on one key, supplied, and 3 pulses on the other.

158
00:18:17,200 --> 00:18:18,160
I reduce further.

159
00:18:24,210 --> 00:18:27,970
0.4% pulse duration.

160
00:18:28,970 --> 00:18:32,470
Here now 0.1%.

161
00:18:32,470 --> 00:18:36,930
That is, you see effectively one signal remained.

162
00:18:38,850 --> 00:18:39,770
Opening.

163
00:18:39,850 --> 00:18:40,930
I add duration.

164
00:18:41,670 --> 00:18:49,070
0.2% at modulation frequency done at frequency 1 kHz.

165
00:18:49,950 --> 00:18:51,890
Such a signal we have.

166
00:18:52,050 --> 00:18:56,950
But if I roll, you see effectively only peak signals remained.

167
00:18:58,170 --> 00:19:01,910
Such is a check of our master logic part.

168
00:19:02,130 --> 00:19:03,690
And we see that it's serviceable.

169
00:19:03,930 --> 00:19:08,210
Now I can switch the switch to continuous generation mode of the scheme.

170
00:19:09,130 --> 00:19:12,370
And return to the original.

171
00:19:12,590 --> 00:19:19,570
After I checked the master logic part, the signal is supplied already to the power part, to the driver.

172
00:19:19,810 --> 00:19:21,950
And I move to its testing.

173
00:19:21,950 --> 00:19:28,730
Now I'll move the oscilloscope to these points, on the FET transistor gates.

174
00:19:29,630 --> 00:19:32,970
And immediately I want to draw your attention to this moment.

175
00:19:33,190 --> 00:19:42,450
That you need to look in the usual mode when we look at the oscilloscope relative to the common wire.

176
00:19:43,110 --> 00:19:51,570
But in half-bridge and bridge systems, in no case can the second probe's common wire be put at this point.

177
00:19:51,950 --> 00:19:59,000
Because you'll short close this transistor through the common probe of the oscilloscope.

178
00:19:59,850 --> 00:20:02,910
And the driver may fail.

179
00:20:03,110 --> 00:20:07,210
Or the power key, if this system is under load.

180
00:20:07,350 --> 00:20:13,610
That is, you do a direct short circuit of the upper-arm key on the common wire.

181
00:20:14,870 --> 00:20:21,210
Now before you is the oscillogram of the driver's work on the power key gates.

182
00:20:21,950 --> 00:20:26,990
You see here some sag on the front edge, that is the gate charging goes for us.

183
00:20:27,130 --> 00:20:33,090
The driver, reminder, is 2-amp at us, not very powerful, so we have such an oscillogram.

184
00:20:34,150 --> 00:20:39,050
The driver works through a 24 Ohm resistance.

185
00:20:39,190 --> 00:20:44,190
I picked it as optimal under these IRF840 transistors.

186
00:20:45,130 --> 00:20:46,730
Here I circled it.

187
00:20:47,730 --> 00:20:51,130
This resistor is marked with an asterisk.

188
00:20:51,230 --> 00:20:55,790
It will generally need to be picked individually under your power keys.

189
00:20:57,250 --> 00:21:01,730
What you choose here in this line from 510 to 840.

190
00:21:02,390 --> 00:21:14,530
This resistance affects driver heating, that is the final current that'll pass when charging the power key gate.

191
00:21:14,530 --> 00:21:17,350
You'll play with this parameter.

192
00:21:17,910 --> 00:21:20,850
The rear edge, you see, is quite sharp.

193
00:21:21,850 --> 00:21:28,170
For this edge the power key gate discharge goes.

194
00:21:28,790 --> 00:21:36,850
And for its sharp discharge is responsible this diode connected counter to the input pulse.

195
00:21:37,390 --> 00:21:41,810
And through it the discharge bypass of this resistance is done.

196
00:21:41,810 --> 00:21:52,910
So you see that the charge of the gate capacity is done more lengthily by time, and the discharge very sharply.

197
00:21:53,670 --> 00:22:05,350
The gate capacity discharges through the diode and inside on the driver's arm is located a forward-reverse transistor.

198
00:22:05,350 --> 00:22:07,630
That is, N-channel and P-channel.

199
00:22:07,730 --> 00:22:14,470
And exactly through the P-channel transistor the discharge of gate capacity to scheme common happens.

200
00:22:15,490 --> 00:22:28,710
This is for the lower key, and here the gate discharge happens to the middle point for the key in the upper arm of our half-bridge.

201
00:22:30,550 --> 00:22:33,950
I convinced myself we have the oscillogram.

202
00:22:34,030 --> 00:22:37,310
Also sweep through frequency, look that the frequency changes.

203
00:22:37,410 --> 00:22:39,710
The driver should react adequately.

204
00:22:39,890 --> 00:22:40,950
Duration changes.

205
00:22:41,070 --> 00:22:47,970
And only after viewing all these parameters can we come to load connection.

206
00:22:48,070 --> 00:22:52,710
Already test in power mode of this scheme on the oscillogram.

207
00:22:52,710 --> 00:22:55,210
We look at the oscillogram now.

208
00:22:55,850 --> 00:22:59,650
The oscilloscope is connected via AC, that is in AC mode.

209
00:23:00,410 --> 00:23:07,410
The initial launch under load of the system is done on a lamp of rating 25 W, 220 V.

210
00:23:07,490 --> 00:23:10,230
I connected it at these points.

211
00:23:10,630 --> 00:23:12,850
Instead of our future inductor.

212
00:23:15,250 --> 00:23:16,850
What's the work algorithm?

213
00:23:16,970 --> 00:23:22,070
Put the oscilloscope on the lamp terminals and observe the oscillogram.

214
00:23:22,710 --> 00:23:26,430
And then smoothly raise the supply voltage.

215
00:23:27,050 --> 00:23:30,350
I'll do this from my lab power supplies.

216
00:23:31,310 --> 00:23:33,990
That is, each one applies what they have.

217
00:23:35,690 --> 00:23:37,290
I raise the voltage.

218
00:23:39,650 --> 00:23:41,710
I start with 50 V.

219
00:23:42,370 --> 00:23:42,790
Watch.

220
00:23:42,990 --> 00:23:47,110
Such an oscillogram we get now during work.

221
00:23:48,990 --> 00:23:53,490
You see the lamp doesn't start glowing.

222
00:23:53,890 --> 00:23:56,570
The consumption is 0.04 A at us.

223
00:23:58,210 --> 00:24:05,870
If you have a lab block, then here it's desirable to set the current protection in an acceptable mode.

224
00:24:06,190 --> 00:24:10,510
